<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-722-070  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 722 070.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Oct 1989 v14 n10 p244(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Joining forces. (optoelectronic technology)(includes relatedarticle on research)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Channin, Donald J.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Optical technology will not replace silicon in futureintegrated-circuit designs but will provide the I/O connectionsnecessary to support greater amounts of logic.andP;  The electricalcharacteristics of current printed wiring boards degrade and limitperformance at clock speeds above 30 MHz, and power-charging linecapacitance grows with frequency.andP;  Light can connect circuitswithout requiring a controlling medium because it is not limitedto the geometries of electronic wiring.andP;  A fewoptical-interconnect subchips could replace hundreds of bondingpads.andP;  Optoelectronic technology uses semiconductors to generatelight signals and to send and receive them before converting themback into electrical form on a single chip.andP;  Problems withinterfacing geometries and with processing and handling diodelasers make optoelectronic components costly, but many enablingtechnologies have emerged.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Optoelectronic devicesResearch and DevelopmentOptical ComputersFuture TechnologiesCircuit Design.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   An optical subchip. (chart)An optoelectronic chip. (chart)Grating surface-emitting laser. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>